reviews.review_text: Sing of death and loss oh Grateful Dead Muse! One of the great Jack Straws they did between the fall of 84 and the spring of 86 lands us into the desert with this stark depiction.  I really like the soundboard the best for this set.  It’s a clean one to thx Charlie Miller!  It allows you to hear the subtleties like Jerry’s final nail in the coffin for poor old Shannon when he sings ‘laid his body down’ in a rebuking tone as if to quickly say “told you so” .  His lead, when it finally finds its way to the mix is fiery and intense.  Peggy-O is spirited and darkly celebratory.   High Time is the showstopper, the most overlooked version and possibly the best version of the year.   I love shows with BIODTL.  That’s the real deal there.   I have to say I’m surprised at the energy of this show b/c our impression of this run on the east coast was reserved only to the second set of the night they played She Belongs to Me which I always considered to be a sleepy set weighed down by tryptophan or some kind of trypo, crypto-something.   Not this one though: three rockers in a row to end the set.  Back in a bit.  Second set opens with what’s probably a continuation of the argument from the first set between Bobby and the drummers except here it sounds a little bit serious and I wonder if that energy will spill over.  It sounds like Bob is not ready and Phil is late.  Oh well.  So they play a song about saying shove it you know where.  I love the 85 Aikos (yeah, east coast) b/c they’re peppy and not as stretched out as they would later get.  84-86 is the heyday imo.  This is a good one , goes along at a clip and has a big confetti rave up at the end.  At this point in things, you’re wondering if Aiko means you’re going to get one of those brisk Estimated>something into drums but it’s Lost Sailor which is getting rare though you don’t know it and that holds promise of another Jerry song before drums.  It’s Terrapin which leads to a chaotic, primal jam and Don’t Need Love.  Is it the first one Jerry plays on? Perhaps.  The post drums has a sweet Stella Blue and an over-the-top Sugar Magnolia that Jerry does about half a minute of scrubbing to close the main section.  U.S. Blues continues the rockin’ theme.
